# Tailwind Styling Best Practices

## Design tokens in one place

- Define **design tokens** in CSS with Tailwind v4’s `@theme` (in `src/styles/global.css` or the layout that loads first).
- Put colors, spacing, fonts, radius, and shadows in `@theme` so they become utilities and CSS variables. Avoid one-off arbitrary values when a token makes sense.

```css
@import "tailwindcss";

@theme {
  --color-bg: #0d0d0d;
  --color-surface: #161616;
  --color-muted: #8c8986;
  --font-sans: 'DM Sans', system-ui, sans-serif;
  --radius-md: 0.5rem;
}
```

- Use **`:root`** only for values that should not generate utilities (e.g. app-only variables). Prefer `@theme` for anything that maps to utilities.

## Prefer utilities; minimal custom CSS

- Style with **Tailwind utility classes** first. Add component-scoped `<style>` or extra CSS only when there is no suitable utility or the same pattern repeats and deserves a single name.
- Keep **global CSS** minimal: `@import "tailwindcss"`, `@theme`, and a small set of base styles (e.g. `html`/`body`). Let the layout and components use utilities.

## Class order and readability

- Order classes in a consistent way: **layout** (flex, grid, block) → **sizing** → **spacing** (margin, padding) → **typography** → **colors/backgrounds** → **borders** → **effects/transition**.
- Prefer **one logical group per line** or a short comment when it helps. Avoid a single unreadable long line of classes.

```html
<!-- Prefer -->
<main class="mx-auto flex min-h-screen max-w-2xl flex-col gap-8 px-6 py-12">
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-[var(--color-text)]">

<!-- Avoid -->
<main class="flex flex-col gap-8 px-6 py-12 mx-auto min-h-screen max-w-2xl">
```

## Semantic HTML + utilities

- Apply utilities on **semantic elements** (main, section, header, nav, article, footer) instead of adding wrapper divs only for styling. Prefer fewer elements and clearer structure.

## Avoid duplicating styles — set on parent when shared

- If a **color, font, or other style** applies to all (or most) children, put it on the **parent** once instead of repeating the same class on every child.
- Prefer **inheritance**: `text-[var(--color-text-muted)]` on a `<section>` so its `<p>`, `<dd>`, etc. inherit; only override on elements that differ.
- Same idea for **font size**, **font family**, or **line-height** on a card or list container so children don’t each need the same classes.

```html
<!-- Prefer: one place for shared color -->
<section class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] text-sm">
  <p>First paragraph.</p>
  <p>Second paragraph.</p>
</section>

<!-- Avoid: same class on every child -->
<section>
  <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] text-sm">First paragraph.</p>
  <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] text-sm">Second paragraph.</p>
</section>
```

## Responsive and theming

- Use **mobile-first** breakpoints: base styles for small screens, then `sm:`, `md:`, `lg:` as needed. Don’t over-specify breakpoints; add them only when the layout or type actually changes.
- If you support dark/light or multiple themes, drive it with **one mechanism** (e.g. `class="dark"` on `html` or `data-theme` on a root element) and use `@theme` / CSS variables or Tailwind’s dark variant so tokens stay the single source of truth.

## Maintainability

- **Reuse tokens** from `@theme` (e.g. `text-[var(--color-muted)]`, `rounded-[var(--radius-md)]`) instead of hardcoding hex or rem values in markup.
- If a repeated pattern grows (e.g. card, link list), extract a **small component** or a single **custom class** in global CSS and use that name instead of duplicating long utility strings. Prefer one shared definition over many copies.
